Well, the grain in the chair (oak?) certainly isn't anything special, so
I'm going to say it originally had that white (Louis XVI ?) gesso? and
gold finish, and someone stripped it and stained it. On top of that,
someone did a lousy job re-upholstering it! &lt;g&gt;

The footstool's inlay looks pretty nice from what I can see of it.

We call the pros &quot;upholsterers,&quot; I think.

For the most part, I think the material something is made of should
speak for itself. If you're going to paint a lovely grained wood, you
might as well have used metal or plastic instead. Conversely, don't
wood-grain a steel front door (which is the fashion here)... it's steel,
dammit, don't try to make it something it's not! &lt;g&gt;

OTOH, I'm the first one to paint over a plain new-growth pine piece when
I've gotten tired of looking at the stained finish. And I usually don't
strip old paint from an older piece before re-painting over it - the
history of the piece is in the layers of paint (assuming it was painted
from Day 1), and I don't want to mess with the lead layers anyway. &lt;g&gt;
But I try to keep a nicely grained older piece's finish intact. I may
use wax or oils, but usually don't try to refinish it unless it's not
that old.

Here's a quick (bad) pic of a 30's kitchen cupboard. Originally it was
white (about 7 layers of it), with black and red stenciling on the
glass. The stencils were nearly gone, so I scraped them off, repainted
it and replaced the hardware.

http://www.ao.net/~chaos/cupboard.jpg

For the most part, wood should look like wood, chrome like chrome,
aluminum, plastic and whatever like what it actually is. In the
cupboard's case above, it was masonite and pine, and was meant to be
painted, so I had some fun with it. But faux finishes have no place in
my home decor! &lt;big grin&gt;

Have fun, Michele
