the polish has had a light rubber added, has been waxed on a regular
basis, maybe twice (or more) a year for many times in its life.
However, this is not the same as a complete refinish or re-polishing
job. If much of this furniture had not be cared for over the years
then it would have deteriorated. If it had not been cleaned (as in
dusted and buffed with a dry wax free cloth) daily it would degrade.
Daily cleaning certainly the common practice in Victorian and
Edwardian times but right into the 50/60s and possibly longer,
depending on the type and status of home where these pieces normally
resided. As well as the daily buffing many of these pieces, as I have
said, received care with waxing, this all added to the finish we
expect to find on good well cared pieces, this is how patina builds.

In real life, all the good Vicky pieces I showed, the years of
accumulated dirt and household air-borne grim which had settled on the
furniture and where the duster never touched or when the duster merely
push it all into all the nooks and crannies was there, in and around
the leg turnings, in the low relief of the carvings, around handles
etc etc precisely what we hope to find. Doesn't matter if one is the
King of the restorers that can not be faked. Deep staining, perfume
spills, ink spills, dents etc., etc., etc., all there. Because the
detail is not shown in the pictures one should not assume. Dressing
table tops did suffer, and suffered heavily over the years, sure many
times the dressing table top had an extra clean, a good waxing or even
a quick refreshing with the rubber, this is NOT refinishing, this is
the life of a dressing table. These folk knew what they had at the
time, they cared for the stuff, either the local cabinetmaker, local
antique dealer even, or if their status had merit, the on-site
carpenter, all helped in the care of the pieces. This is a different
can of worms.

Most re-polished furniture that turns up here, is obvious, if it has
been stripped and polished, as usually, the grain is lying open and
has NOT been properly grain filled. Shows no sign of accumulated dirt
and grim. With stuff like this the polish just sits there glistening
within the grain, absolutely dreadful looking stuff and a million
