touch with the rubber you lose bits of the original finish and are in
effect refinishing with a new one. You are right that most people regard
refinishing as stripping off the old finish, patina and all down to the
bare wood, but it is possible to completely refinish a piece and leave
the original finish intact without stripping, all that is required is a
proper cleaning of the surface gunge and a recoat with the same type of
finish as the original. Solvent release type finishes like shellac bond
by melting together, the new finish melds with the old at the surface,
the colour and old finish remain intact. Even the grime of ages in the
nooks and crannies remains intact because spirit varnishes like shellac
will seal right over them. I have brought back spirit finishes that had
begun to powder by spraying alcohol over the surface to get it to flow
out and then French polished it with a tinted shellac with wonderful
results. It can be done, but few will spare the time to learn or care
enough to bother over here.
