muted ones we like to see on period furniture, but finishes that have
obviously been recoated with more modern materials some 50 to 80 years
ago and exhibit crazing indicative of such materials. It has got to the
point here that 150 year old painted country pieces are left in the
rough with their eighty year old peeling paint on because &quot;it's
original&quot;, formal pieces refinished in the 1950's exhibit just enough
wear to pass in a lot of shops as &quot;original&quot; and the public eats it up.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt; See how far you go with this. New unpolished wood tends to have
&gt; uniformity of colour. The difference between hard areas like knots,
&gt; burrs, flecks, hard grains and soft areas of straight grain and
&gt; sapwood can be accentuated by adding polish.

"/> The old boys ran into most of the same problems craftsmen do today, most
wood types require dyes to make the colour uniform from one board to the
next, today we use dyes dissolved in a number of solvents for quick
drying. 18th century and early 19th century craftsmen used a variety of
vegetable dyes to get the colour they wanted, Alkanet root mixed with
oil produced a strong red colour, barberry root makes a good yellow,
logwood could be used with a variety of mordants to produce, red , brown
, black or blue colours. The old boys had many more dye &amp; stain sources
used to bring out the grain in figured veneers or match sapwood to
heartwood ,but they all were subject to fading.

Linseed was one of the

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; oils used which sank into the wood in different degrees and, with
&gt; added colour, helped accentuate distinctions and thus made the piece
&gt; more interesting. Sheraton went so far as to suggest the use of
&gt; powered brick dust. The result was polished and often varnished, and
&gt; the owner was encouraged to see that a wax polish was applied and
&gt; rubbed well in. This kept the piece clean and added to the protective
&gt; layer, often accurately referred to by dealers as 'skin', which in
&gt; turn oxidised.

"/> The brick dust mixed with oil works well as an abrasive /filler, the
French used pumice in place of brick dust ( I still do) the dust
polishes the surface by levelling the surface,the slurry of wood dust
,brick dust and oil fills the grain, sometime a dye would be added to
even the colour. Linseed oil has the advantage over most surface
finishes as it actually penetrates the surface of the wood to some
degree, but still ,like you say, requires regular maintenance by waxing
or recoating.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt; However, this hard, impervious, protective layer served another
&gt; function. The bleaching effect of strong light gradually wastes out
&gt; the colouring in the gain, producing different shades, and varies with
&gt; the type of wood. The oil being applied in new polishing cannot
&gt; permeate the patina (the gloss produced by age) so the bleaching
&gt; effect continues slowly and at different rates on the surface.

"/> Well yes and no, if the finish is degraded or worn oil will penetrate
and change the colour, most conservators no longer recommend the use of
linseed oil as a polish because of it's tendency to darken finishes and
collect dust.
The bleaching effect ,as you say, does carry on no matter what finish
you use, even the most modern finish with UV retardants are only good
for about 3 years.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

